pgsql

In the root of your project folder, create:

json
{
  "name": "butterfly-bcs-server",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "bcs_server.js",
  "scripts": {
    "start": "node bcs_server.js"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.18.2"
  }
}

Run this to install dependencies:

bash
npm install

If you haven’t already:

bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial BCS server commit"
gh repo create butterfly-chat --public  # or private
git push -u origin main

🌐 4. Connect to Vercel

  1. Go to vercel.com

  2. Import your GitHub repo

  3. When asked for the framework preset, choose Other

  4. Set the build command to:

    arduino
    npm install && npm run start

  5. Set the output directory to:

    cpp
    public

Here’s a clean, foolproof walkthrough to push your local project to GitHub from VS Code:

🧭 Step-by-Step: Push Your Existing Project to GitHub

✅ 1. Make sure you're in the correct project folder

Open the terminal in VS Code (Ctrl + ~ or View > Terminal), and check:

bash
git status

If you see something like:

vbnet
On branch main
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.

You’re already connected. If not, read on.

🆕 2. If no remote is set: Create a GitHub repo

  • Go to GitHub

  • Name it (e.g., butterfly-chat)

  • Choose Public or Private

  • DO NOT initialize with README

🔗 3. Link your local repo to GitHub

Back in your terminal:

bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/butterfly-chat.git

(Replace with your GitHub link.)

📦 4. Add + Commit Files

If you haven’t done this yet:

bash
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

☁️ 5. Push to GitHub

If you’re using the main branch (common with new repos):

bash
git push -u origin main

If it says fatal: The current branch has no upstream branch... then use:

bash
git push --set-upstream origin main

🧠 Troubleshooting Common Issues:

ErrorFix
remote origin already existsRun git remote remove origin then re-add it
Authentication failedMake sure you’re logged into GitHub via VS Code (or use a Personal Access Token if prompted)
Permission denied (publickey)You're using SSH instead of HTTPS; either switch to HTTPS or configure your SSH key with GitHub

If you get stuck, paste the exact error message here and I’ll walk you through it in real-time.
